Here's a basic implementation using C++ and the `boost::algorithm` library for string manipulation. This example assumes you have the Boost library installed, which can be downloaded and installed from the [official Boost site](https://www.boost.org/).

First, ensure you include the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <boost/algorithm/string.hpp>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/replace.hpp>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/case_conv.hpp>
```

Then, define the function `markdownToHTML`:

```cpp
std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string& markdownText) {
    // Basic Markdown to HTML conversion
    // This is a simplified version and does not cover all Markdown features.

    // Convert to lowercase for easier processing
    std::string text = boost::to_lower_copy(markdownText);

    // Headers
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "# (.*)\\n", "<h1>$1</h1>");
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "# (.*)\\n (.*)\\n", "<h2>$1</h2>$2");

    // Bold and italic
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "** (.*) **", "<strong>$1</strong>");
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "_ (.*) _", "<em>$1</em>");

    // Unordered Lists
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "* (.*)", "<li>$1</li>");

    // Hyperlinks
    boost::algorithm::replace_all(text, "(http://.*)|(https://.*)", "<a href=\"$1\">$1</a>");

    // Return the processed string
    return text;
}
```

This function demonstrates how to convert basic Markdown elements to HTML. Here's a quick breakdown of what it does:

- **Headers**: It converts `#` followed by text to `<h1>` for the first header and `<h2>` for subsequent headers.
- **Bold and Italic**: It wraps text between `**` for bold and `_` for italic with `<strong>` and `<em>` tags, respectively.
- **Unordered Lists**: It converts each line starting with a `*` to an `<li>` item in an unordered list.
- **Hyperlinks**: It finds URLs and wraps them with `<a>` tags, assuming they are complete URLs.

To use this function, include it in your program and call it with a string containing Markdown:

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Header 1\n\n**Bold Text**\n_Italic Text_\n\n*Item 1\n*Item 2\n\n[Example Link](http://example.com)";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHTML(markdownText);

    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This example is quite basic and intended for educational purposes. For more complex Markdown to HTML conversions, consider using existing libraries or frameworks designed for this purpose, such as those available in Python or JavaScript, which are more fully featured for parsing and rendering Markdown.

